shortTermOutlook.stateDescription: Recent bearish events outweigh bullish events.

msBullishSummary: As the largest player in NGL market, Enterprise is most leveraged to petrochemical demand in the Gulf Coast and international markets.
Its expansion into petrochemical activities insulates Enterprise from midstream cyclicality.
Enterprise’s marketing activities let it extract additional fees from its asset base while providing insights into each of its markets.
msBearishSummary: The marketing operations depend on differential spreads that could continue to narrow without investments by Enterprise and third parties to spur demand.
If the promise of a large increase in NGL demand from China and India in particular never materializes, Enterprise is left holding the bag with export facilities.
Without substantial growth in U.S. hydrocarbons, more of Enterprise's assets risk being underutilized and thus seeing lower revenue and fees.

reports.reportTitle: Wednesday was a nice change of pace from the drudgery of falling stock prices, skyrocketing rates, and the soaring U.S. dollar. In a well-timed release (as SPX futures were getting hit overnight, and the greenback was higher, and strategists were worried that the gilt market would seize up, and many markets were stretched), the Bank of England came to the rescue. The BOE said that it was buying unlimited amounts of long-dated bonds to help stabilize markets after gilt yields soared and the pound slumped to a record low in the wake of last Friday's U.K. budget announcements. The BOE also postponed a planned sale of gilts for next week.

reports.reportTitle: Literally everything seems to be going against the stock market. Rising yields across the curve, a strong dollar (which no one seems to be talking about), surging crude oil prices along with gasoline and heating oil, and a Fed that must start taking liquidity out of the system. Oh, and let's not forget about the war, continued supply issues, and stubborn inflation. Did we miss anything? Ah, yes. A breakdown in mega-growth stocks, an absolute collapse in hyper-growth stocks, a massive drawdown in cryptos, and broad economic worries.

reports.headHtml: Weekly Stock List
reports.reportTitle: Markets have faced difficult times before, with challenging economic environments, wars, disease, banking and housing crises, and inflation much worse than we are seeing now, to name but a few. Of late, stock investors had it very good for a very long time -- but now, finding opportunities requires much more work. There is no secret sauce, but there are principals that are worth reviewing: 1) diversify; 2) look for strong management; 3) look for solid balance sheets; 4) do your homework; and 5) adapt. To assemble this week's list, we looked across several sectors that historically are considered to be the most-shielded from high inflation and high interest rates. We then cross-referenced our coverage universe for companies where our analysts recently raised target prices; that have an Argus Financial Strength rating of at least Medium-High; and that pay dividends of least 3%. Some companies also are featured in our model portfolios (Growth & Income, Equity Income, Growth, and Institutional). Here is our list of companies we believe to be recession-proof, all of which are rated BUY at Argus.

reports.headHtml: Weekly Stock List
reports.reportTitle: We recently raised our rating on the Energy sector to Over-Weight from Market-Weight. Already strong demand for petroleum products (related to global reopening) is now exacerbated by the war in Ukraine, which has led to broad sanctions on Russia and may exclude this major supplier from the global energy markets. Although we expect other counties to add to supply, we expect energy prices to remain elevated at least through year-end. Energy accounts for 3.6% of S&P 500 market cap; over the past five years, the weighting has ranged from 2% to 10%. We think investors should consider allocating 4%-5% of diversified portfolios to the group. The sector is outperforming thus far in 2022, with a gain of 32.3%. It also outperformed in 2021, with a gain of 47.7%. It underperformed in 2020, with a loss of 37.3%, and in 2019, with a gain of 7.6%.  Here are some of the Energy sector companies that are on our BUY List. Some also are featured in our model portfolios (Growth & Income, Equity Income, Growth, and Institutional) and in our Focus List.

reports.headHtml: Daily Spotlight: Insiders are Cautious
reports.reportTitle: Insider sell/buy ratios from Vickers Stock Research reflect a cautious outlook from corporate insiders. The neutral range for these readings is between 2.00 and 2.50, and things are bearish above 2.50. This week, Vickers' NYSE/ASE One-Week Sell/Buy Ratio sits at 4.61 and the Total one-week result (which adds in transactions on the Nasdaq) is 3.89. Those are not frightening readings, but they are clearly cautious. Of particular interest, insiders at technology companies that often list on the Nasdaq had been the most cautious for the past month. That made sense, as the shares of those companies (generally) have led the charge higher since the March lows and there was a lot of money on the table. But this week, those same insiders are clearly less cautious than their peers at the blue chips firms that typically are found on the NYSE.  By the numbers, the one-week sell/buy reading for the NYSE is 5.42, while the same figure at the Nasdaq is a markedly lesser 3.48. One might infer that blue chip businesses have much more to fear from a resurgence in coronavirus than do newer, technology-based companies that help people work at home, shelter at home, and have everything they need delivered to home.

reports.headHtml: Daily Spotlight: Insiders Step Up
reports.reportTitle: Stocks remain on a wild ride that mostly goes down. Yet something else also is taking shape: exceedingly bullish insider sentiment in the midst of broader market pain. When the market carnage first started, corporate insiders looked the massive selling right in the eyes and responded by buying. Now, with the stock-market decline gaining momentum, insider-sentiment data from Vickers Stock Research again shows that insiders are gobbling up shares. As well, the volume of insider transactions is very high, giving additional weight to the sentiment that comes from those transactions. Vickers' Total One-Week Sell/Buy Ratio is now 1.35, very positive on a scale where anything below 2.00 is bullish. Vickers' Total eight-week moving is now 2.88, and has improved from 4.76 a mere two weeks ago. We acknowledge that (most) insiders are not doctors and their current enthusiasm in no way reflects an imminent end to the coronavirus. But assuming this health crisis follows the same path to resolution as those that came before it, insiders seem to see current value in stocks.

reports.headHtml: Market Update: PRU, SHW, SKX, BHP, EBAY, EPD, PM
reports.reportTitle: Stocks fell on Friday morning despite a strong January employment report. However, the Labor Department also said that the U.S. economy created 514,000 fewer jobs in the year ended March 2019 than it initially reported. January nonfarm payrolls rose by 225,000, up from a revised 147,000 in December and above the Reuters consensus forecast of 160,000. The official unemployment rate edged up to 3.6% from 3.5%. The S&P fell 0.3%, the Dow 0.5%, and the Nasdaq 0.3%. Crude oil fell slightly to $51 per barrel, while gold rose $2.50 to $1572 per ounce.

reports.headHtml: Technical Assessment: Bullish in the Intermediate-Term
reports.reportTitle: All the major metals, including gold, silver, and platinum, broke their three-month downtrends in early December, thanks to the breakdown in the U.S. Dollar Index. Based on the size of their completed bases and the potential that the current Elliott Wave count is only an ABC or three-wave advance (and not a five-wave move), the current rally could mark the end of the current advance.

reports.headHtml: Market Update: ABBV, ADM, EPD, HES, X
reports.reportTitle: An early recovery rally faded on Tuesday, a day after Monday's sharp selloff, as the U.S.-China trade war continued to escalate. The People's Bank of China acted to stabilize the yuan after allowing it to drop on Monday, but said that the U.S. decision to label China a currency manipulator would 'cause chaos in financial markets... and prevent a global economic and trade recovery.' The Chinese Commerce Ministry also announced that Chinese companies would stop buying U.S. agricultural products in retaliation against President Trump's latest tariff threat. The Dow rose 0.1%, the S&P 0.2%, and the Nasdaq 0.3%. Crude oil fell slightly to $54.50 per barrel, while gold rose $7 to $1484 per ounce.

reports.reportTitle: Stocks fell on Wednesday morning, led by declines in the Communication Services, Real Estate, and Consumer Discretionary sectors. Videogame maker Electronic Arts fell nearly 14% after posting disappointing fiscal 3Q results and lowering its full-year revenue guidance. Competitors Take-Two Interactive and Activision Blizzard also fell sharply. The Dow fell 0.1%, the S&P 0.2%, and the Nasdaq 0.3%. Crude oil rose 1% to about $54 per barrel, while gold fell $3 to trade near $1316 per ounce.
